observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management require:
The Property/Supply Officer to prepare and submit duly accomplished Report on the Physical Count of Inventories;
The Accountant to properly record the purchases of inventories for consumption or distribution in the appropriate inventory accounts and the consumption or distribution thereof as expense, upon receipt of SSMI of a given period;
The Accounting Unit to maintain supplies ledger cards and the Local Treasury Unit or the General Services Office to maintain stock cards as required in both their offices; and
Both the Accountant and the Supply Officer to conduct periodic reconciliation of their records and make adjustment, when necessary, to reflect the true balance of the Inventory Accounts in the FS.

We recommended the following to the Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to reclassify items under PPE accounts that falls below the capitalization threshold of ₱15,000.00 to proper inventory account and to recognize expense upon issuance and tender of corresponding Inventory Custodian Slip to the end-user for proper monitoring, control and accountability;
Direct the Inventory Committee to continuously make utmost effort to conduct a complete and detailed physical inventory of all the LGU’s properties in accordance with the new guidelines and procedures prescribed by COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31 2021, prepare and submit, within the deadlines set, the RPCPPE together with the RPCRNS of the LGU and reconcile the results of the count with the property and accounting records in accordance with Section C.3, Chapter V of the Manual on Property Custodianship;
Instruct the General Services Officer to prepare and maintain the Local Road Inventory Map and Property Cards for each type of properties as basis for reconciliation with the PPE accounts with the accounting records;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain, in relation to the local road networks of the LGU, Local Road Network Ledger Card (LRNLC), including the regular property ledger cards, also as basis for reconciliation with the GL account balances and with the property records;
Execute a deed of donation to recipient schools of buildings, equipment and other PPE donated by the LGU and to draw a JEV dropping off the respective PPE accounts in the LGU’s books of accounts and transmit it to the respective divisions or autonomous schools together with other documents relative to the buildings and other PPE items to enable their Accountant or Bookkeeper to record it in their books of accounts;
Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all depreciable assets are provided with depreciation and draw a journal entry voucher to take up unrecorded current and prior years’ depreciation expense to present fairly the FS in accordance with IPSAS 17; and
Require the GSO and Municipal Accountant to initiate the reconciliation of their respective records and avail the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, strictly in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 and adjust the books accordingly, in order to come up with a reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Prepare and submit liquidation reports of outstanding fund transfers received from various agencies which purposes were already completed, and return any unspent amount and henceforth, strictly adhere with the provisions of Section 4 of COA Circular No. 94-013 dated December 13, 1994 and Section 3.1.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated June 14, 2012;
If the disposition of the unspent/unutilized amount is not provided in the MOA, Trust Agreement or Memorandum of Understanding, the agency may, at their option, utilize the said amount by sending a letter to the source agency requesting approval to transfer the unexpended balance to the General Fund .(Section 3.2 of COA Circular 2012-001);
Fast track the implementation of the fund transfers since the resources are readily available, and in order not to deprive the Municipality of the PPAs where the funds are intended for; and
Reconcile the Due to NGAs account and take up the necessary correcting/adjusting entries for fair presentation in the FS.

We recommended that Management:
Pursue the implementation of projects and activities as planned in accordance with the mandates of RA No. 10121 and consistent with the National Government’s earnest efforts to enable LGUs and communities in being disaster-prepared and resilient;
Strictly adhere to the state policy on DRRM by giving priority on the implementation of planned LDRRMF PPAs to avoid delay on its implementation;
Observe judicious management of DRRM funds, to include planning, budgeting, and reporting that is geared towards being disaster-prepared and resilient and be in line with the government’s effort to curtail/eliminate/mitigate the spread of COVID-19 in the community; and
Comply with the submission of the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF as well other provisions on the reporting and utilization of DRRMF, as provided in COA Circular No. 2012-002 and Section 6 of JMC No. 2013-1, in order to monitor compliance with accounting and reporting of the sources and Utilization of LDRRMF.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Strictly adhere to the public bonding law of the government and refrain from granting CAs in excess of the maximum cash accountability;
Undertake periodic monitoring of cash accountabilities of the SDOs and increase the bonds, if necessary;
Instruct the staff assigned in monitoring the CAs to ensure that no CAs are granted in case of existing unliquidated CAs;
Stop the practice of granting multiple CAs;
Determine the whereabouts of former employees and demand the liquidation of their accountabilities;
Enforce strictly the liquidation of CAs within the prescribed period and ensure that all CAs are liquidated at the end of each year; and
Verify the collectability of unliquidated CAs of more than 10 years, otherwise, request the authority to write-off dormant accounts guided by the conditions and procedures prescribed under COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Submit the supporting documents on all the recorded obligations in the Accounts Payable account;
Exert effort to prepare and maintain complete subsidiary ledgers for the said account under all funds;
If the balances could not be substantiated after all remedies were resorted, request for the write-off of account balances in accordance with the prescribed procedures; and,
Ensure that all obligations are duly supported with complete documents to prove the validity of the claims before recording it in the books as Accounts Payable or any liability account.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Budget Office to make a systematic and realistic forecasting of revenue taking into account prior years’ experience and statistics as aids in setting targets;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to undertake a review of the present budgeting done under the stewardship of the Municipal Budget Office to set a clearer guide for the concerned revenue generating Departments toward attaining the targets set;
Require the Municipal Treasurer and other Departments involved in generating revenues to meet its targets by conducting periodic review of collection performance by the concerned officials to ascertain whether collection targets are attained; and to analyze the reasons for the shortfall in collections and find alternative solution to minimize, reduce or avoid incurrence of shortfall in the future; and
Require the Municipal Budget Office to provide targets for revenue accounts without projected revenues by setting targets based on statistics, prior years’ experiences and future expectations.

We recommended that Management:
Expedite the completion/updating of the 10-Year Municipal SWM Plan for approval by the NSWMC to serve as guide for the efficient management of solid waste generated within the Municipality’s jurisdiction;
Prioritize SWM programs and projects by providing/allocating enough budget for their full implementation;
Encourage and provide needed assistance to the remaining 18 barangays to establish their own MRFs for the collection, segregation, recycling of biodegradable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes;
Provide the necessary training for SWM collectors and other personnel directly dealing with collection of solid waste to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and the risk of hazards to them and to the public are avoided or minimized; and
Exert continuous effort in preserving and protecting the environment by implementing the environmental laws as mandated under RA No. 9003.

We recommended that Management:
Develop a comprehensive program for each community based programs/activities, formulate policy guidelines and design appropriate internal controls and monitoring activities for the program’s implementation to ensure its sustainability and proper utilization of government funds;
Review and prioritize all programs that will give maximum benefits for the constituents and discontinue those that do not cater the basic needs of the constituents;
Provide budget for each departments/offices on their own community based programs, streamline GAD budget in accordance with existing rules and regulations; and
Submit status and accomplishment reports to the Office of the Mayor, copy furnish the COA Audit Team, for monitoring and decision making purposes.

We recommended that Management:

a. Require all drivers and concerned officials to completely fill up the Driver’s Trip ticket in accordance with existing regulation for transparency and accountability over the use of such government motor vehicles;

b. Prepare and submit Monthly Report of Official Travels and Monthly Fuel Consumption Report of LGU vehicles and heavy equipment to the Commission on Audit (thru Municipal Accountant) for verification and evaluation of the Auditor within 10 days of the ensuing month;

c. Establish and implement effective control over the use of government vehicle and fuel, oil and lubricants consumption to prevent wasteful, excessive and unnecessary expenditures; and

d. Advice the Accountant to make appropriate accounting entries in recording fuel, oils, and lubricants expenditure for the current year and previous years, if allowed.

We recommended the following: a. That the Office of the Municipal Accountant give preferential and utmost attention on the preparation and submission of the required bank reconciliation statements pursuant to Section 474 of RA No. 7160 and COA Circular No. 96-011 dated October 2, 1996 considering that the variance had already reached a significant amount of ₱25,778,627.89;

b. The Municipal Treasurer exert efforts in maintaining an updated cashbooks for all Cash In Bank accounts. The data reflected in the cash books of the Municipal Treasurer must preferably be considered in the preparation of the bank reconciliation statements to ensure that any reconciling items will be accordingly adjusted; and

c. Any error and reconciling item discovered in the reconciliation process must   accordingly be adjusted in the respective records which need correction/revision, to arrive at the correct and reliable cash in bank balance.

We recommended the following to the Management:

a. Comply with the provisions of DBM/NEDA/NCRFW Joint Circular No. 2004-1 to appropriate at least 5 percent of their total budget appropriations for GAD programs, projects and activities; 

b. Stop the practice of realigning GAD funds to augment the budget of LGU’s other programs, activities, projects without implementing the predetermined GAD activity for such fund; 

c. Strengthen the Municipality’s gender-responsive governance and fully utilize the allocation thereon; and 

d. Utilize the GAD Fund only for acceptable programs, projects and activities that would address the identified gender issues in the locality.

We recommended the following to the Management:

a. Intensify the collection of tax and non-tax revenues from local sources; 

b. Require the Municipal Treasurer with the help of the Municipal Assessor, to create strategies to increase collection of delinquent RPT taxes; 

c. Apply the available remedies for collection of Real Property Tax (RPT) provided by the IRR of R.A. No. 7160; and 

d. Appropriate/budget within the reasonable or attainable estimates so as not to come up with negative appropriation and target goal collections that is possible.
